To      all~
Subject Flight 232~
Text
``  Soaring high over the Pacific, a metallic bird shines brightly in the 
afternoon sun. Below, the ocean waters are as still as glass. The calmed
surface looks like one large pane of blue glass, stretching out into
infinity.

``  "This is your captain, speaking. We will be arriving in San Francisco
around 3 o' clock in the afternoon. But, in the meantime, you can watch
our in-flight movie, 'A Beautiful Mind', which will start shortly. The
stewardesses will be selling the headphones for you to listen to the
movie while they bring around today's lunch. We hope that you enjoy the
rest of your flight." The speakers in the cabin gave a soft click, and
were silent.
``  The creaks of the large steel carts rolling down the carpet filled the
air with the soft voices of the plane's crew, conversing with the
passengers. "We have ham and cheese, and grilled chicken."
``  The passenger looked up from behind the brim of his top hat with a wide
smile. "I'll pass, thank you."
``  "Not hungry?" the girl gave a quaint smile.
``  "Yes, but I just don't feel like having anything just yet."
``  The stewardess gave him a puzzled look, then shrugged. "Well, hopefully
you packed something yourself," she said, trying to be cheerful.
``  The man only chuckled, and watched her continue down the aisle.

``  The movie screen descended and the image of the day's movie began to
flicker into existence. The man had no headphones, but his grin widened
in anticipation... the carts were nearly at the front of the plane now.
``  The words "A Beautiful Mind" appeared on the screen just as the carts
came to the head of the plane, and the man began to unbuckle his seatbelt.
With his free hand, he took the handle of his lion-headed cane and 
sauntered down the aisle.
``  One of the stewardesses turned around and smiled. "Did you change your 
mind, sir?"
``  He returned an equally bright grin. "Yes."
``  The other stewardess opened the door to the cockpit, holding today's
lunch. The dark skeleton put a clammy hand on the woman's shoulder.
The one speaking to him stuttered, "Uh-um sir, you're not supposed to--"

``  The door to the cockpit closed. David turned around once the cart caught
the corner of his eye. "Ah, so what's on today's menu, Wend... y?"
``  A man dressed in a black dress suit from the 19th century gave a slight
bow. "Ham and cheese, or grilled chicken?"
``  The co-pilot lunged for the phone, but was met with the blunt end of a
quick moving lion effigy.
``  "Jesus!" David, the captain, fumbled for his gun desperately.
``  A metal spike drove deep into Dave's heart, and all life flowed out of
him like silk passing through one's fingers.
``  The third man in the cockpit put the attacker into a headlock. "You son
of a--!" The lion arced through the air and struck him in the back of the
head. He released his grip on the man and collapsed.

``  The man looked around himself and shook his head solemnly. "Really, just
because it was on rye." He searched the panel with his eyes. "But then again, 
I like sourdough better, myself." He reached out and flicked the switch that 
read, "Auto-Pilot"... "And cooking the meat just wastes time." His thin, pale 
face twisted into a cruel sense of utter, sick joy.

``  Ten minutes later, Flight 232 was gone.
~
