Sender  Maiser~
Date    Tue Apr 30 20:47:49 2002~
Stamp   1020217669
To      all~
Subject Anime and Charecters.~
Text
The topic of course being in line with what anime charecters we enjoy the most because we find ourselves with alot in common. There are many reasons to like a charecter. I picked out three examples from the most outstanding anime of each type.
The primary examples will fall into three arbitary catagories with perhaps a fourth. The main three are people that we wish to be, people that we admire, and people we think we are.
Admire and wish to be are harder to distinguish. To set things straight, this is mostly the cool charecters that hold appeal in thier style, class, skill, or another factor that isn't something we consider ourselves.
They infact are designated under unattainable wants.
The charecter we wish to be is admired for traits that we find in ourselves. When we look at thier story, we can put ourselves in thier place and be satisfied that thier personality is our outcome as well.
That is beyond the now, and that leaves the charecter we think we are. The person who defines our existance at the current time. More often then not, hes an Otaku of some sort.
`@Spike Speigel`7 from `!Cowboy Bebop`7 and `@Yomiko Readman`7 from `!Read or Die`7 both fall into the admire catagory.
While they fall near some of the cliche charecters of other anime, they in fact are more like real people in that there is subtlety or originality that works with the well established charecter type
and creates an extreamly memorable charecter.
`$While by and far the best example may be `!Kenshin`$ of this, he doesnt hold my focus as much as `!Spike`$ or `!Yomiko``
`!Spike`7 exemplifies 'cool'. The bounty hunter with a past in the mafia, `!Spike`7 lives an exotic life in a sort of underworld of free thinkers and loveable freaks.
This instantly grabs at the image of the hero that is set in my mind. The name `@Cowboy Bebop`7 is a perfect description of this free sprit.
In that way Spike portrays a wild person that lives a vibrant and dangerous life. The excitment and fringe lifestyle and extroversion make him a charecter that I find worth watching.
`!Yomiko `7 from the yet unreleased `@Read or Die`7 OAV series is quite the oppisite. A quiet book loving introvert who happens to be a secret agent for her special powers
She is both innocent and kind and beyond geeky, without being comical in the manner that shes presented.
Both charecters go far beyond the sort of existance that I think I would fit. However that they appeal to these extreams with unique persona makes them excellent charecters.
`!Folken`7 from my favorite series `@The Vision of Escaflowne`7 is a cold calculating charecter who seems to be unreadable if not entirely inhuman.
however the appeal of the charecter is that as you learn more about him, and as he grows you see another side to him.
To some extent the charecter lends himself the darker side of rational thinking appeals to those who also have used manipulation or see the idea behind ends 'justify the means'
In other words, the charecter that works for the good at the end, not the easy way now.
The last charecter is `!Keitaro`7 from `@Love Hina`7. Hes trying to get into collage, but every test seems to go wrong. He is in love with a hard studying member of the all girls dorm he manages...
The 'nerd in love whos really a nice guy but just gets into situations that mess him up' is a stock charecter. However with the creative writing and development that goes into love hina's story
`!Keitaro `7doesn't come off as boring or hashed over but, rather, a new take on something thats familiar as stratospheric punting of  perverts
Overall the best charecters have elements that we can associate with. They represent the dreams or the ideals of the common person. Even the complex charecters are idealised.
Good charecters that are both new and old, and that grow, draw us into the anime we watch. Its not as important that they have super powers or are super human
More so that as they make thier way through their story we find they in fact are people that we think we could be.
~
