Quirks:
When he shapeshifts, the action rebounds upon Ruka, forcing her to become
a wolf while he is human. Her fur is the same red brown as her hair, and
she is much smaller, reflecting her smaller stature.
Bleeds liquid fire, stabbing and slicing weapons do no damage to him, save
that when he loses too much blood, he weakens considerably, which weakens
Ruka as well. Bludgeoning weapons can hurt him, and any physical damage
that he takes reflects upon his mistress. For instance, if he is hit over
the head, if the blow is hard enough, Ruka will fall unconcious. If he is
kicked in the nose, her nose will also bleed.
If either of the two perishes, the other will follow suit.
He is vulnerable to holy magic, life magic has normal effect upon him, and
he can absorb fire and unholy magic. Water and ice magic are draining to him.
As with shapeshifting and physical damage, absorbing energy also reflects
upon his mistress, much of the extra energy backlashes through her, which
has different effects depending on the circumstances. In all cases, an over-
dose of energy will begin to cause her physical damage, and eventually kill
her.
Salamander and Ruka can not be physically and mentally out of contact for
more than a day without causing them harm. Ruka's life energy begins to
drain away, and Salamander begins to overload on it as he produces much
more than he actually uses.

(The nature of Salamander and Ruka's bond is that Salamander produces the
energy that Ruka lives on in order to survive. All of the rebound effects
are due to this close energy bond. He produces more than Ruka can use, so
she must burn the energy off somehow, which usually ends up being either
sex or violence.)

All in all, I consider him to be more of a detriment than an asset, although
in the correct circumstances, he can be very useful.

Forgot: He can shapeshift into other forms than human, with no ill effect
to Ruka.
