Sender  Daltigoth~
Date    Fri Sep 27 00:37:28 2002~
Stamp   1033105048
To      all~
Subject Beginnings.~
Text
ooc- Heh, this is actually much compressed from its original format.
In future weeks here I am going to start a webpage with a more complete history,
and compilation of the various stories I have written following the various Daltigoth's and my other
characters. Why? Feh, just because. Anyway. For the moment, here is my return.


The young man pulled the wire from his datajack, a smirk on his face.
His cybernetic eyes gleamed in the dim light of the warehouse, and he idly
watched a rat run through some shadows in the corner, from one crate to
another.

He thought back over his orders. They had been delivered in the usual manner.

"Use the memories and experiances of the previous Daltigoth. He was softhearted,
and his failure has caused his death. All that was his, is now yours, weapons,
memories, powers, all of it. You would be wise to avoid following his lead, unless
you too wish to suffer his fate. Don't think you can go rogue, like that sociopath,
Alpha. We will find him, his pain shall be unmatched in duration, and severity,
as will his death."

Somewhere in the distance, a police siren began to wail. The roof of the
warehouse began to rattle as a soft rain commenced. Daltigoth yawned,
baring sharp teeth, and slowly stood. He thought back on the rest of his
orders as he packed his few belongings into the saddlebags strapped across
his old motorcycle.

"Explore this place. Do not allow any information on MadenTek to be exposed, at
all costs. Infiltrate the local Societies. Do not allow the population of this
world to be destroyed. Deaths of those who are ...inconvenient... are acceptable,
even expected, however."

The orders had droned on for some period after that. Daltigoth smirked to himself.
Those fools at MadenTek. They thought they could control him, use him. He had
learned much from the old Daltigoth. And from that psycho Alpha, for that matter.
He walked over, and toed the corpse of the contact once more. He put his
shotgun to the back of it's head and pulled the trigger one more time, just to make
sure. It had been remarkably difficult to kill. 

He strode over to the wreckage of the portal device, and checked the explosives 
over one more time. He whispered to the empty warehouse: "Another world lost to
you, MadenTek. How many more, I wonder, can you afford to lose? You are like a 
snake without its head. Without your leader, you are nothing." His thoughts drifted 
to that man. The one he had joined MadenTek to follow. The one whose disappearance 
has caused MT's rapid downward spiral. A report he had hacked out of the corp's
database, before he had wiped it, suggested that his spirit might be re-incarnated
in this world.

The sirens in the distance began to sound as if they were getting closer, and
the storm began to heavily pound the old warehouse. He strode over to his motorcyle,
and got on. He rode out into the dark and rain, his engine roaring. He wondered
to himself, why he had decided to stay in this place. Perhaps the fond memories
the old Daltigoth had of this place had influenced him. Or perhaps the thought
of once again meeting the entity who had lead MadenTek. Or maybe this just looked
like a place worth spending his life. Only time would tell.

For now, he had a decision to make. Yet another clandestine organization 
hell bent on ending all life on the planet had appeared. He considered the
samples he had managed to collect, and the fragmentary information he had access
to. He would have to find friends to help deal with this, one way or another.

"Long live the Kronos Tuerater," he muttered to the night. He pushed the button
on the small remote device in his hand. Several blocks away, an earth shaking
explosion went off, completely levelling the old warehouse in a massive fireball.
He shivered in the darkness, as cold rain began to work its way down the back of
his neck. He rode into the streets of the city, looking for a drink, and a warm
place to sleep.
~
